---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { estimateApr } from "../../lib/calc/apr";

const title = "Interest Rate vs APR Calculator (what to compare)";
const description =
  "How to compare interest rate vs APR, when APR is more informative, and how to estimate APR with fees using a calculator. Educational use only.";

const exampleLoanAmount = 300000;
const exampleRate = 6.5;
const exampleTermMonths = 360;
const exampleFees = 6000;
const base = estimateApr({ loanAmount: exampleLoanAmount, nominalRatePercent: exampleRate, termMonths: exampleTermMonths, fees: 0 });
const withFees = estimateApr({
  loanAmount: exampleLoanAmount,
  nominalRatePercent: exampleRate,
  termMonths: exampleTermMonths,
  fees: exampleFees
});
const money = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
const pct = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
const num1 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 1 });
const breakevenFees = 3000;
const breakevenMonthlySavings = 80;
const breakevenMonths = breakevenMonthlySavings > 0 ? breakevenFees / breakevenMonthlySavings : null;
const breakevenYears = breakevenMonths == null ? null : breakevenMonths / 12;
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/interest-rate-apr-calculator">
  <section class="card hero">
    <span class="pill">Guide</span>
    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/guides">Guides</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">Interest rate vs APR calculator</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>Interest rate vs APR calculator</h1>
    <p>
      The interest rate drives the payment and interest. APR can include certain upfront fees, which can make two "same-rate" offers have
      different true costs. This page explains what to compare and how to model it.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn" href="/topics/apr">APR topic hub</a>
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/apr-calculator">APR calculator (include fees)</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/apr-vs-interest-rate">APR vs interest rate</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">What APR does (and doesn't) capture</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Think of <strong>interest rate</strong> as the input that drives your interest charges and principal-and-interest payment. In
      contrast, <strong>APR</strong> is designed as a broader comparison metric that can reflect certain upfront finance charges (like
      origination fees or discount points) by converting them into an annualized rate over the stated term.
    </p>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>APR is best</strong> when two offers have different lender fees but the same term.</li>
      <li><strong>APR is less representative</strong> if you refinance, sell, or prepay well before the term ends.</li>
      <li><strong>APR is not total cost</strong>: taxes, insurance, and many third-party closing costs may not be included.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Use APR as a filter for fee-heavy offers, then sanity-check with the monthly payment and a break-even calculation for your expected
      time horizon.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">When APR is the better comparison</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>When one offer has higher origination fees or points.</li>
      <li>When you want an apples-to-apples cost metric across offers with the same term.</li>
      <li>When you plan to keep the loan long enough that upfront fees matter.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Example: same rate, different fees</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Two lenders can quote the same interest rate but different upfront fees (origination fee, points). The monthly payment can look
      similar, but the fee changes your total cost and can raise APR. Use the APR calculator to estimate how much the fee changes the
      effective borrowing cost under the same term.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:12px">
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/apr-with-origination-fee">APR with origination fee</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/apr-calculator-payment">APR and monthly payment</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="grid" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">How to model it</h2>
      <ol class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
        <li>Use the same term across offers.</li>
        <li>Enter loan amount, interest rate, term, and fees.</li>
        <li>Compare estimated APR and payment.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">Common pitfalls</h2>
      <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
        <li>Comparing APR across different terms.</li>
        <li>Ignoring whether fees are paid upfront vs financed.</li>
        <li>If you refinance early, APR may be less representative.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Worked example (estimate)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Example inputs: {money.format(exampleLoanAmount)} loan, {exampleRate}% rate, {exampleTermMonths} months.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Scenario</th>
            <th class="num">Fees</th>
            <th class="num">Monthly payment (P&amp;I)</th>
            <th class="num">Estimated APR</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>No fees</td>
            <td class="num">{money.format(0)}</td>
            <td class="num">{money.format(base.payment)}</td>
            <td class="num">{base.aprPercent == null ? "N/A" : `${pct.format(base.aprPercent)}%`}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>With fees</td>
            <td class="num">{money.format(exampleFees)}</td>
            <td class="num">{money.format(withFees.payment)}</td>
            <td class="num">{withFees.aprPercent == null ? "N/A" : `${pct.format(withFees.aprPercent)}%`}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      In this example the payment is identical, but APR rises because the fee reduces the net amount received.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Break-even (time horizon) matters</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      If you might refinance or repay early, the cheapest APR over the full term isn’t always the cheapest option for your time horizon.
      A simple way to sanity-check fee trade-offs is break-even months:
    </p>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Monthly savings = old payment - new payment (keep assumptions consistent).</li>
      <li>Break-even months = upfront fees ÷ monthly savings.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Example: if fees are {money.format(breakevenFees)} and the lower-rate offer saves {money.format(breakevenMonthlySavings)}/month, the
      break-even point is about{" "}
      <strong>{breakevenMonths == null ? "N/A" : `${num1.format(breakevenMonths)} months`}</strong>
      {breakevenYears == null ? "" : ` (${num1.format(breakevenYears)} years)`}.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Use this as a cross-check alongside APR so you’re not paying large fees for savings you won’t keep long enough to realize.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Checklist: what to compare (US loan offers)</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Same term:</strong> compare 30-year vs 30-year (APR across different terms is not apples-to-apples).</li>
      <li><strong>Same loan type:</strong> fixed vs fixed, ARM vs ARM; note if rates are introductory.</li>
      <li><strong>Fees and credits:</strong> list origination fee, discount points, and any lender credits.</li>
      <li><strong>Cash needed at closing:</strong> ensure you can afford it without draining emergency savings.</li>
      <li><strong>Prepayment rules:</strong> confirm whether there is a prepayment penalty (or any restrictions).</li>
      <li><strong>Time horizon:</strong> estimate how long you'll keep the loan and compare to break-even months.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">FAQ</h2>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Is a lower APR always better?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      Not always. APR is a useful comparison metric, but you still need to consider your time horizon, the cash needed at closing, and
      whether the quoted offers are truly comparable (same loan type, term, and assumptions).
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Why can two offers have the same rate but different APR?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      APR can reflect certain finance charges. If one lender charges higher upfront fees or points, your effective borrowing cost increases
      even if the note rate is the same.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Can APR be lower than the interest rate?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      It's uncommon, but lender credits (or certain fee structures) can sometimes make the effective cost lower than the note rate under a
      specific set of assumptions. Use a calculator to sanity-check the scenario.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Should I compare APR on adjustable-rate mortgages (ARMs)?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      You can, but be careful: APR depends on assumptions about future rates and may not reflect your actual path. Focus on the initial
      period, caps, and worst-case payment scenarios, then use APR as a secondary check.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">References</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>
        CFPB:{" "}
        <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/ask-cfpb/what-is-apr-en-63/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          What is APR?
        </a>
      </li>
      <li>
        Federal Reserve:{" "}
        <a href="https://www.federalreserve.gov/boarddocs/supmanual/cch/200806/1020a.htm" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          Regulation Z (Truth in Lending) overview
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:10px">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/apr-calculator">Estimate APR with fees</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/apr-with-origination-fee">APR with origination fee</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/how-to-find-your-apr">How to find your APR</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/refinance-break-even">Break-even (time horizon)</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">Educational use only. Not financial advice.</p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; font-size:13px">Last updated: 2026-01-27</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
